  "tips": [
    {
      "id": 1,
      "topic": "owoc_countable",
      "content": "'Owoc' is a countable noun in Polish. You can use it in the singular for one piece of fruit and in the plural for some fruit.",
      "examples": [
        "owoc = a piece of fruit",
        "owoce = some fruit"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "topic": "sprzedawac_present_tense",
      "content": "The verb 'sprzedawać' (to sell) is irregular in the present tense.",
      "tables": {
        "present_tense": {
          "ja": "sprzedaję",
          "ty": "sprzedajesz",
          "on_ona_ono": "sprzedaje",
          "my": "sprzedajemy",
          "wy": "sprzedajecie",
          "oni_one": "sprzedają"
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "topic": "zdrowy_vs_niezdrowy",
      "content": "The opposite of 'zdrowy' (healthy) is 'niezdrowy' (unhealthy)."
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "topic": "asking_price_patterns",
      "content": "To ask the price of an item or items, you can use either 'W jakiej cenie jest/są...?' or 'Po ile jest/są...?'",
      "examples": [
        "W jakiej cenie jest ten ananas? = What's the price of this pineapple?",
        "W jakiej cenie są banany? = What's the price of the bananas?",
        "Po ile jest chleb? = How much is the bread?",
        "Po ile są truskawki? = How much are the strawberries?"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 6,
      "topic": "forming_plural_nouns_and_adjectives",
      "content": "The book gives a quick reminder that plural nouns and adjectives often depend on the last letter of the singular form. All plural adjectives end in -e.",
      "examples": [
        "jabłko -> jabłka",
        "gruszka -> gruszki",
        "owoc -> owoce",
        "arbuz -> arbuzy",
        "duże, małe"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 9,
      "topic": "te_here",
      "content": "In this context, 'these' translates as 'te'."
    },
    {
      "id": 10,
      "topic": "green_vs_black_grapes",
      "content": "In Poland, you can buy 'jasne winogrona' (green grapes, literally light grapes) or 'ciemne winogrona' (black grapes, literally dark grapes)."
    },
    {
      "id": 11,
      "topic": "taste_adjectives",
      "content": "Useful adjectives to describe taste:",
      "examples": [
        "słodki = sweet",
        "kwaśny = sour",
        "słony = salty",
        "gorzki = bitter",
        "ostry/pikantny = spicy",
        "łagodny = mild"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 13,
      "topic": "czy_jestes_pewny",
      "content": "To a man, say '(Czy) jesteś pewny?' or '(Czy) jesteś pewien?'. To a woman, ask '(Czy) jesteś pewna?'."
    },
    {
      "id": 15,
      "topic": "lista_zakupow",
      "content": "'lista zakupów' means 'shopping list'. The English word 'list' and Polish 'list' are false friends: Polish 'list' means 'letter'."
    },
    {
      "id": 16,
      "topic": "infinitive_for_should_or_shall",
      "content": "You can use the infinitive alone in this context to express English 'should' or 'shall'. Another option is 'mieć + infinitive + object'.",
      "examples": [
        "Kupić chleb? = Should/Shall I buy some bread?",
        "Mam kupić chleb? = Should I buy bread?"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 17,
      "topic": "poczestuj_sie",
      "content": "'Poczęstuj się!' or 'Częstuj się!' means 'Help yourself!'."
    }
  ],
